{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York City", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{for|effects of the pandemic in the state|2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York (state)}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in New York City}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 COVID-19 pandemic in New York City\n| width           = \n| image           = File:USNS Comfort passing by Statue of Liberty, March 30, 2020.png\n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = The {{ship|USNS|Comfort}} passing by the [[Statue of Liberty]] in [[New York Harbor]] on March 30\n| map1            = COVID-19 outbreak New York CSA per capita cases map.svg\n| legend1         = Confirmed cases per 10,000 residents in the greater New York City area\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[New York City]]\n| first_case      = [[Manhattan]]\n| arrival_date    = mid-February<ref name=EuropeanOrigin>{{cite news|title=Most New York Coronavirus Cases Came From Europe, Genomes Show|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/08/science/new-york-coronavirus-cases-europe-genomes.html|last=Zimmer|first=Carl|publisher=New York Times|date=2020-04-08|accessdate=2020-04-09}}</ref><br>{{small|(first case found March 1)}}<ref name=March1/>\n| date            = \n| confirmed_cases = {{Unbulleted list\n  |198,988 ([[New York metropolitan area#Combined statistical area|CSA]]; Apr 8)<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 Cases US |url=https://www.arcgis.com/home/item.html?id=628578697fb24d8ea4c32fa0c5ae1843 |website=www.arcgis.com |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326155740/https://www.arcgis.com/home/item.html?id=628578697fb24d8ea4c32fa0c5ae1843 |archive-date=March 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n  |94,409 (NYC; Apr 10)<ref name=\"nyc_gov_data\">{{cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/site/doh/covid/covid-19-data.page|title=COVID-19: Data - NYC Health|website=nyc.gov|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401235417/https://www1.nyc.gov/site/doh/covid/covid-19-data.page|archive-date=April 1, 2020|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>}}\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = 25,920 (Apr 10)<ref name=\"nyc_gov_data\" />\n| recovery_cases  = \n| deaths          = 5,429 (Apr 10)<ref name=\"nyc_gov_pdf\">{{cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/doh/downloads/pdf/imm/covid-19-daily-data-summary-04102020-2.pdf|title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) - Daily Summary|url-status=live|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|http://www.nyc.gov/coronavirus}}\n}}\n\nThe first [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] case was confirmed in [[New York City]] in March 2020 in a woman who had recently traveled from [[Iran]], a country seriously affected by the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|2020 coronavirus pandemic]] at the time. Nearly a month later, the [[New York metropolitan area|metropolitan area]] was the worst-affected part of the [[United States]], with its medical infrastructure overtaxed.<ref name=\"nyti_Coro\">{{Cite news|last1=Goldstein|first1=Joseph|last2=McKinley|first2=Jesse|title=Coronavirus in N.Y.: Manhattan Woman Is First Confirmed Case in State|work=The New York Times|date=March 1, 2020|page=A24|access-date=March 25, 2020|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/01/nyregion/new-york-coronvirus-confirmed.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302012003/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/01/nyregion/new-york-coronvirus-confirmed.html|archive-date=March 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"npr._NewY\">{{cite web| title = New York City, U.S. Epicenter, Braces For Peak| author = | work = NPR| date = March 24, 2020| access-date = March 26, 2020| url = https://www.npr.org/2020/03/24/820610818/new-york-city-u-s-epicenter-braces-for-peak| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200326185342/https://www.npr.org/2020/03/24/820610818/new-york-city-u-s-epicenter-braces-for-peak| archive-date = March 26, 2020| url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== March ===\nOn March 1, 2020, the first case of [[COVID-19]] was confirmed in [[New York State]], a 39-year-old woman [[health care worker]] who lived in [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]].<ref name=March1>{{Cite news|last=West|first=Melanie Grayce|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/first-case-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-new-york-state-11583111692 |title=First Case of Coronavirus Confirmed in New York State|date=March 2, 2020|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=March 9, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303050256/https://www.wsj.com/articles/first-case-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-new-york-state-11583111692 |archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> She had returned from [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iran|Iran]] on February 25, and did not have any symptoms at the time. She went into [[home isolation]] with her husband.<ref>{{cite news |title=New York's first case of coronavirus is a health care worker, and officials say more cases are 'inevitable' |first=Holly |last=Yan |first2=Kristina |last2=Sgueglia |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/02/us/new-york-coronavirus-first-case/index.html |newspaper=CNN |date=March 2, 2020 |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200304002946/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/02/us/new-york-coronavirus-first-case/index.html |archive-date=March 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBy March 25, there were over 17,800 confirmed cases in New York City, and 199 deaths.<ref name=\"nyti_DeBl\">{{cite news| title = De Blasio Calls Stimulus Deal's Treatment of N.Y.C. 'Immoral'| author = | work = nytimes.com| date = March 25, 2020| access-date = March 25, 2020| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/nyregion/coronavirus-new-york-update.html#link-17e20485| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200325112712/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/nyregion/coronavirus-new-york-update.html#link-17e20485| archive-date = March 25, 2020| url-status = live}}</ref> The New York City region was suffering from an [[infection rate]] 5 times higher than the rest of the country, and was the worst-hit district in New York State due to its population density, 56% of known national cases were in New York State,<ref name=\"50 percent\">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NBCNews/status/1242107530463019011?s=19 |title=NBC News twitter message|last=|first=|date=March 23, 2020|website=|publisher=[[NBC News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date= |access-date=March 23, 2020|quote=5,707 new coronavirus cases in New York state, Gov. Cuomo announces, bringing state total to 20,875, representing more than half of all US cases}}</ref> with one-third of total known US cases being in New York City.<ref>{{cite news|last=Perlstein|first=Mike |url=https://www.wwltv.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/perl-stats-story/289-f2e70da4-3e5b-48b5-8684-a0dd5dc0361d |title=New Orleans is second only to Seattle in COVID-19 cases per capita|date=March 16, 2020|newspaper=4WWL|accessdate=March 16, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200317192439/https://www.wwltv.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/perl-stats-story/289-f2e70da4-3e5b-48b5-8684-a0dd5dc0361d |archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDuring the month of March, the [[United States Army]] dispatched soldiers from [[United States Army Corps of Engineers|Army Corps of Engineers]] field hospitals in [[Fort Campbell, Kentucky]], and [[Fort Hood, Texas]], to New York City to convert the {{convert|1800000|ft2|adj=on}} [[Javits Center]] into a 2,910-bed civilian medical hospital.<ref name=mashcivilian>{{cite web|url= https://www.militarytimes.com/news/your-military/2020/03/27/the-army-corps-of-engineers-has-two-or-three-weeks-to-get-thousands-of-new-hospital-beds-up-and-running/ |title=The Army Corps of Engineers has two or three weeks to get thousands of new hospital beds up and running|first=Meghann|last=Myers |date=March 27, 2020|website=Military Times|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200330090248/https://www.militarytimes.com/news/your-military/2020/03/27/the-army-corps-of-engineers-has-two-or-three-weeks-to-get-thousands-of-new-hospital-beds-up-and-running/ |archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> More medical hospitals would be set up by these Army officers in New York City.<ref name=mashcivilian />\n\nOn March 27, infection in New York City surpassed 23,000, with 365 deaths including a nurse in Manhattan and a civilian staff member in the [[New York City Police Department]] (NYPD). [[The Bronx]] had 80 deaths (22% of total deaths in NYC); [[Brooklyn]], 81 (22% of total deaths in NYC); Manhattan, 55 (15% of total deaths in NYC); [[Queens]], 123 (34% of total deaths in NYC); and [[Staten Island]], 26 (7% of total deaths in NYC). A large majority of those who died had underlying health issues.<ref name=\"nyti_N.Y.\">{{cite news| title = N.Y.C. Death Toll Hits 365 as Case Count Tops 23,000| author = | work = nytimes.com| date = March 27, 2020| access-date = March 28, 2020| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/26/nyregion/coronavirus-new-york-update.html | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200328045217/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/26/nyregion/coronavirus-new-york-update.html| archive-date = March 28, 2020| url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 28 it was reported that at least 156 [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]] workers including chairman [[Pat Foye]] had tested positive, while 1,181 were [[self-quarantine]]d.<ref>{{cite news |authors=Clayton Guse |title=MTA chairman Pat Foye tests positive for coronavirus |url=https://www.nydailynews.com/coronavirus/ny-coronavirus-mta-chairman-pat-foye-positive-covid-19-20200328-ku7qifgu2rdi5o4dr5plntgp2i-story.html |publisher=New York Daily News |date=March 28, 2020 |access-date=March 29, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200329110908/https://www.nydailynews.com/coronavirus/ny-coronavirus-mta-chairman-pat-foye-positive-covid-19-20200328-ku7qifgu2rdi5o4dr5plntgp2i-story.html |archive-date=March 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBetween March 28 and 29, the number of deaths in New York City tripled from the previous 24-hour period; 222 people died of the virus bringing the city's fatalities to 672, with 30,765 confirmed cases. Instead of quarantining the city, the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] urged residents in New York, [[New Jersey]], and [[Connecticut]] to refrain from non-essential travel to other states for a period of 14 days.<ref>{{cite news |authors=Jen Chung |title=Coronavirus Updates: 222 COVID-19 Deaths Reported In NYC Over 24 Hours |url=https://gothamist.com/news/coronavirus-updates-222-coronavirus-deaths-nyc-over-24-hours |work=Gothamist |date=March 29, 2020 |access-date=March 29, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200329145514/https://gothamist.com/news/coronavirus-updates-222-coronavirus-deaths-nyc-over-24-hours |archive-date=March 29, 2020 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On March 29, [[CBS News]] reporter [[Maria Mercader]], a New York City resident, died from a COVID-19 related illness.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/video/remembering-cbs-news-journalist-maria-mercader/ |title=Remembering CBS News journalist Maria Mercader|accessdate=March 31, 2020|via=www.cbsnews.com|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200330235009/https://www.cbsnews.com/video/remembering-cbs-news-journalist-maria-mercader/ |archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/tv/2020/03/29/coronavirus-cbs-news-maria-mercader-dies-covid-19-age-54/2936246001/ |title=CBS mourns longtime journalist Maria Mercader, who died at 54 from coronavirus|first=Hannah|last=Yasharoff |website=USA TODAY|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200331021320/https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/tv/2020/03/29/coronavirus-cbs-news-maria-mercader-dies-covid-19-age-54/2936246001/ |archive-date=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[President Trump]] implied on March 29 that there was a black-market for medical equipment in New York City, complaining that [[mask]] usage, which had increased from 20,000 to 300,000 in a week, was \"worse than hoarding.\" \"Where are the masks going, are they going out the backdoor?\" Trump asked. Surgical or [[N95 mask]]s can protect the wearer from 95% of airborne particles and are essential to protecting the health of doctors, nurses, and other health-care providers.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/trump-claims-masks-needed-coronavirus-021110138.html Trump claims masks needed for coronavirus are 'going out the backdoor' of NYC hospitals by the thousands] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330052913/https://news.yahoo.com/trump-claims-masks-needed-coronavirus-021110138.html |date=March 30, 2020 }} by James Pasley, Insider, March 29, 2020</ref> Questioned by [[CNN]]'s [[Jake Tapper]] on ''[[State of the Union]],'' if he thought his messaging may have had something to do with how fast the [[virus]] had spread in the city, Mayor [[Bill de Blasio]] said \"none of us have [sic] time to look backward\" and we should concentrate on next week.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/bill-blasio-says-isnt-time-145900084.html Bill de Blasio says there isn't time to focus on coronavirus prevention missteps] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331040341/https://news.yahoo.com/bill-blasio-says-isnt-time-145900084.html |date=March 31, 2020 }} by Tim O'Donnell, The Week, March 29, 2020</ref>\n\nThe {{ship|USNS|Comfort}} hospital ship arrived in [[New York Harbor]] on March 30.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-live-updates-us-death-093743203.html Coronavirus live updates: USNS Comfort arrives in NYC; Anthony Fauci defends extension of social distancing rules; US deaths top 2,500] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330094014/https://news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-live-updates-us-death-093743203.html |date=March 30, 2020 }} by John Bacon, USA TODAY, March 30, 2020</ref> It was also announced that [[field hospital]]s would be set up in [[Central Park]] in Manhattan and at the [[Billie Jean King National Tennis Center]] in Queens.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/30/824300407/central-park-and-home-of-tennis-us-open-to-house-hospital-beds-for-new-york |title=Central Park And Home Of Tennis' U.S. Open To House Hospital Beds For New York|first=Anastasia|last=Tsioulcas |publisher=NPR|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200331113326/https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/30/824300407/central-park-and-home-of-tennis-us-open-to-house-hospital-beds-for-new-york |archive-date=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> At hospitals such as [[Lenox Hill Hospital]] on the [[Upper East Side]] of Manhattan, [[Refrigerator truck|sidewalk morgues]] were set up on city streets to deal with the overflow of corpses from the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/health/surge-in-deaths-overwhelms-new-yorks-morgues-hospitals |title=Archived copy |access-date=April 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403041350/https://www.pbs.org/newshour/health/surge-in-deaths-overwhelms-new-yorks-morgues-hospitals |archive-date=April 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 31, it was revealed that New York Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]]'s brother [[Chris Cuomo]], who serves as a [[Cuomo Prime Time|CNN journalist]] and is a New York City resident, was diagnosed with COVID-19, and that the first death of a child from COVID-19 in New York City was recorded.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/e80a98f37714622c5b34d27d94bea8ff |title=NYC sees 1st child virus death; Chris Cuomo tests positive|agency=Associated Press|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331150103/https://apnews.com/e80a98f37714622c5b34d27d94bea8ff |archive-date=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:COVID19_Shuttered_Retailers_Unionport_-_The_Bronx_NY.jpg|thumb|Non-Essential retailers closed in Unionport, [[The Bronx]]]]\n\n=== April ===\nOn April 4, Cuomo announced that the Chinese government had arranged for a donation of 1,000 ventilators to be sent to New York through foundations run by [[Jack Ma]] and [[Joseph Tsai]].<ref name=\"ny0404\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/04/nyregion/coronavirus-new-york-update.html#link-696ea085 |title=Coronavirus Hot Spots Emerging Near New York City |date=April 4, 2020 |publisher=The New York Times}}</ref> The state of Oregon was reported to be sending 140 ventilators.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/news/2020/04/04/governor-cuomo-presser-4-4-2020 |title=Cuomo: 1,000 Ventilators Arriving From China, 140 From Oregon|date=April 4, 2020|publisher=NY1}}</ref> Trump announced that 1,000 additional federal medical soldiers would be deployed to NYC.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.news12.com/story/41973252/president-trump-1000-military-personnel-deploying-to-nyc-to-help-in-covid19-hot-zone |title=President Trump: 1,000 military personnel deploying to NYC to help in COVID-19 hot zone |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> It was reported that \"Urban Area Medical Task Forces\" made up of army [[reservists]] would be working in arenas and convention centers that are serving as temporary field hospitals in NYC and other parts of the country.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/03/politics/us-military-additional-forces-coronavirus/index.html |title=US military preparing to deploy additional forces to support coronavirus response|date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> {{As of|2020|4|4|df=US|alt=As of April 4}}, there were 1,200 medical military personnel serving on the USNS ''Comfort''. 2,700 [[New York State National Guard]] forces had also been deployed.<ref name=\"ny0404\" />\n\nOn April 5, it was reported that a tiger at the [[Bronx Zoo]] had contracted COVID-19, the first known case of a tiger anywhere being infected with the disease. Several other \"big cats\" were found to have COVID-19, the first of which had started showing symptoms on March 27; they were believed to have contracted COVID-19 from an infected zookeeper [[asymptomatic carrier|who was not yet showing symptoms]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Health/wireStory/tiger-nycs-bronx-zoo-tests-positive-coronavirus-69989185 |title=Tiger at NYC's Bronx Zoo tests positive for coronavirus|last1=PELTZ|first1=JENNIFER |date=5 April 2020|website=[[ABC News]]|language=en}}</ref> This is also the first known case of an animal contracting the disease from human contact in the US.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/animals/2020/04/tiger-coronavirus-covid19-positive-test-bronx-zoo/#close |title=Tiger tests positive for coronavirus at Bronx Zoo, first known case in the world |publisher=Nationalgeographic.com |date=2020-03-30 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nAs of April 8, at least 80% of New York City virus patients put on ventilators had died.<ref>[https://apnews.com/8ccd325c2be9bf454c2128dcb7bd616d]</ref> Some of the communities most affected by the pandemic include densely-populated neighborhoods in north-central Queens with high immigrant populations, including [[Corona, Queens|Corona]], [[East Elmhurst, Queens|East Elmhurst]], [[Elmhurst, Queens|Elmhurst]], and [[Jackson Heights, Queens|Jackson Heights]]. {{As of|2020|April|8|alt=As of April 8}}, these communities, with a cumulative 600,000 residents, had recorded 7,260 COVID-19 cases.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Correal|first=Annie|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/09/nyregion/coronavirus-queens-corona-jackson-heights-elmhurst.html|title=\u2018A Tragedy Is Unfolding\u2019: Inside New York\u2019s Virus Epicenter|date=2020-04-09|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-09|last2=Jacobs|first2=Andrew|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Jones|first3=Ryan Christopher}}</ref>\n\nOn April 11, Mayor Bill de Blasio announced that schools remain closed for the rest of the year.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/11/nyregion/nyc-schools-closed.html</ref>\n\n==Social distancing==\n\nOn March 28, a Brooklyn bar owner, 56-year-old Vasil Pando, was arrested for defying Governor Andrew Cuomo's ban on bars and restaurants until April 15. Pando was charged with \"illegal sale of alcohol, promoting gambling, and violating the mayor's {{sic|expected=governor's}} order\".<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-york-speakeasy-bar-owner-135650349.html Coronavirus: New York bar owner becomes first to be arrested for ignoring lockdown] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331140449/https://news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-york-speakeasy-bar-owner-135650349.html|date=March 31, 2020}} by Gino Spocchia, The Independent, March 30, 2020</ref>\n\nOn March 30, the mayor announced that most religious buildings had shut down in accordance with quarantine regulations. However, he warned that some churches and synagogues were not in compliance and would be shut down by authorities if they remained open.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.jpost.com/Diaspora/NYC-Mayor-to-synagogues-Close-for-coronavirus-or-be-shut-down-permanently-622767|title=NYC mayor to synagogues: Close for coronavirus or shut down permanently|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|accessdate=March 31, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330194032/https://www.jpost.com/diaspora/nyc-mayor-to-synagogues-close-for-coronavirus-or-be-shut-down-permanently-622767|archive-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn April 3, the NYPD broke up a party in the Bronx where several dozen people had gathered in violation of social distancing rules. Two men were arrested and charged with multiple violations, while dozens more were given a summons for violation of social distancing rules.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2020/04/04/nypd-busts-bronx-party-ignoring-coronavirus-social-distancing-rules/|title=Cops bust boozy Bronx party ignoring coronavirus social distancing rules|date=April 4, 2020|publisher=New Yor Post}}</ref>\n\n==Response by sector==\n{{seealso|2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York (state)}}\n[[File:Coronavirus sign in Brooklyn (60539).jpg|thumb|Woman wearing a mask walks under the Cobble Hill Cinemas in [[Brooklyn]], which closed as a non-essential business.]]\n\nOn March 2, Mayor de Blasio [[Twitter|tweeted]] that people should ignore the virus and \"go on with your lives + get out on the town despite Coronavirus\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/de-blasio-haunted-by-weeks-old-tweet-urging-people-to-get-out-on-the-town-despite-coronavirus |title=De Blasio haunted by weeks-old tweet urging people to 'get out on the town despite coronavirus' |date=March 25, 2020 |first1=Madison |last1=Dibble |work=[[Washington Examiner]] |access-date=March 28, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329063537/https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/de-blasio-haunted-by-weeks-old-tweet-urging-people-to-get-out-on-the-town-despite-coronavirus |archive-date=March 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 7, [[Governor of New York|Governor]] [[Andrew Cuomo]] declared a [[state of emergency]] in New York State after 89 cases had been confirmed in the state, 70 of them in [[Westchester County]], 12 in New York City, and 7 elsewhere.<ref name=\"state-emergency\">{{cite news |last= |first= |date=March 8, 2020 |title=Coronavirus in N.Y.: Cuomo Declares State of Emergency |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/07/nyregion/coronavirus-new-york-queens.html |work=The New York Times |location= |access-date= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309082540/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/07/nyregion/coronavirus-new-york-queens.html |archive-date=March 9, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 9, Mayor de Blasio announced that there were 16 confirmed cases of COVID-19 in New York City.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/news/2020/03/09/new-york-city-coronavirus-case-numbers-health-update|title=Mayor: 16 Coronavirus Cases Confirmed in City|website=ny1.com|language=en|access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, as the number of confirmed cases rose to 814 citywide, Mayor de Blasio announced that the city was considering a [[shelter-in-place]] order within the next 48 hours. Across the [[boroughs of New York City]], there were 277 confirmed cases in Manhattan, 248 in Queens, 157 in Brooklyn, 96 in the Bronx, and 36 in Staten Island. Seven city residents had died of the virus.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/politics/2020/03/17/new-york-coronavirus-latest-will-new-york-city-have-to-shelter-in-place-be-on-lockdown|title=De Blasio: New Yorkers Should Prepare for Possible Shelter-in-Place Order in Next 48 Hours|date=March 17, 2020|work=Spectrum News NY1|access-date=March 17, 2020|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317221121/https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/politics/2020/03/17/new-york-coronavirus-latest-will-new-york-city-have-to-shelter-in-place-be-on-lockdown|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Public health===\n[[File:JNYMS Operations (1).jpg|thumb|Medical personnel receive and screen a patient]]\nOn January 26, 2020, over a month before the first coronavirus cases were detected in the New York City area, [[Commissioner of Health of the City of New York|New York City Commissioner of Health]] [[Oxiris Barbot]] said at a press conference: \"We are encouraging New Yorkers to go about their everyday lives and suggest practicing everyday precautions that we do through the flu season\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Goldstein|first=Joseph |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/27/nyregion/new-york-city-coronavirus.html |title=New York Braces for Coronavirus: \u2018It's Inevitable\u2019|date=January 27, 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 29, 2020|last2=Singer|first2=Jeffrey E.|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200329201605/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/27/nyregion/new-york-city-coronavirus.html |archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On February 2, Barbot stated \"There is no reason not to take the subway, not to take the bus, not to go out to your favorite restaurant.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fox5ny.com/news/coronavirus-fear-affecting-chinatown-businesses |title=Coronavirus fear affecting Chinatown businesses|date=February 3, 2020|website=FOX 5 NY|language=en-US|access-date=March 29, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200227122827/https://www.fox5ny.com/news/coronavirus-fear-affecting-chinatown-businesses |archive-date=February 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> At a press conference on March 3, Barbot said \"We are encouraging New Yorkers to go about their everyday lives\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.silive.com/news/2020/03/coronavirus-risk-remains-low-in-nyc-same-day-testing-now-available-officials-say.html |title=Coronavirus risk \u2018remains low\u2019 in NYC; same-day testing now available, officials say |date=March 3, 2020 |first1=Kyle |last1=Lawson |accessdate=March 28, 2020 |work=[[SILive.com]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328185143/https://www.silive.com/news/2020/03/coronavirus-risk-remains-low-in-nyc-same-day-testing-now-available-officials-say.html |archive-date=March 28, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 4, she said: \"There\u2019s no indication that being in a car, being in the subways with someone who\u2019s potentially sick is a risk factor.\"<ref name=\"nypost1\"/>  On March 20 Barbot warned that masks should only be used by people who are showing symptoms, saying: \"The time to use a mask is when someone is symptomatic, when they\u2019re coughing, when they\u2019re sneezing, and it\u2019s to ensure that that individual doesn\u2019t contaminate other folks. It gives people who are asymptomatic a false sense of security that if they wear this mask, they don\u2019t have to wash their hands, they don\u2019t have to cover their mouths and their noses when they cough or they sneeze.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Curtis Brodner |url=https://bklyner.com/no-mask-no-gloves-no-service-brooklyn-businesses-start-to-turn-away-customers-without-masks/ |title=No Mask, No Gloves, No Service: Southern Brooklyn Businesses Start to Turn Away Customers Without Masks |work=Bklyner |date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref> New York City Councilmen Democrat [[Robert Holden (politician)|Robert Holden]] and Republican [[Eric Ulrich]] wrote to Mayor de Blasio asking him to relieve Barbot of her position \"before it\u2019s too late,\" saying her guidance on coronavirus had been disastrous.<ref name=\"nypost1\">{{cite web|last=Edelman |first=Susan |url=https://nypost.com/2020/04/04/nyc-pols-urge-de-blasio-to-oust-health-commissioner-over-coronavirus-response/ |title=NYC pols urge de Blasio to oust health commissioner over coronavirus response |work=New York Post |date=April 4, 2020 |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the increasing number of coronavirus cases at the end of March 2020, several [[field hospital]]s were built or proposed, including at the Javits Center (2,910 beds,<ref name=mashcivilian/> including 1,000 non-COVID beds) in Manhattan,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/army-helps-make-temporary-hospital-yorks-javits-center/story?id=69845568 |title=Army helps make temporary hospital at New York's Javits Center one of the largest in the country|last=Martinez|first=Luis |date=March 27, 2020|website=ABC News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200329231758/https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/army-helps-make-temporary-hospital-yorks-javits-center/story?id=69845568 |archive-date=March 29, 2020|access-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> [[USTA Billie Jean King National Tennis Center]] (350 beds) in Queens,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Honan|first=Katie|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/queens-stadium-to-be-converted-into-temporary-hospital-in-coronavirus-fight-11585605068 |title=Queens Stadium to Be Converted Into Temporary Hospital in Coronavirus Fight|date=March 30, 2020|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=March 30, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200331001258/https://www.wsj.com/articles/queens-stadium-to-be-converted-into-temporary-hospital-in-coronavirus-fight-11585605068 |archive-date=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and in [[Central Park]] (68-bed COVID respiratory care unit) in Manhattan.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.whec.com/national/central-park-houses-hospital-ward-as-ny-races-to-add-beds/5690659/ |title=Central Park houses hospital ward as NY races to add beds |publisher=WHEC.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bisnow.com/national/news/healthcare/the-scramble-is-on-to-build-temporary-healthcare-space-103661 |title=The Scramble Is On To Build Temporary Healthcare Space|website=Bisnow}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/30/us/new-york-coronavirus-cases-deaths/index.html |title=Central Park becomes a field hospital for New York, where coronavirus deaths have topped 1,000|last=Holcombe|first=Madeline |last2=Yan|first2=Holly |date=March 30, 2020|publisher=CNN|access-date=March 30, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200330123931/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/30/us/new-york-coronavirus-cases-deaths/index.html |archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Field hospitals were also proposed at the [[New York Expo Center]] in the Bronx, [[Aqueduct Racetrack]] in Queens, the [[Brooklyn Cruise Terminal]], and the [[College of Staten Island]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amny.com/coronavirus/governor-calls-on-federal-government-to-authorize-more-field-hospitals-in-new-york-city/ |title=Governor calls on federal government to authorize more field hospitals in New York City|date=March 27, 2020|website=amNewYork|access-date=March 30, 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200329055138/https://www.amny.com/coronavirus/governor-calls-on-federal-government-to-authorize-more-field-hospitals-in-new-york-city/ |archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Navy hospital ship the USNS ''Comfort'' docked at Pier 90 on the [[Hudson River]] on Manhattan's west side with 750 non-COVID beds.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/coronavirus-patients-delivered-comfort-ship-new-york-mistake |title=Coronavirus patients delivered to hospital ship Comfort in New York by mistake: US officials |publisher=Fox News |date=2020-03-30 |accessdate=2020-04-05}}</ref> Dr. [[David L. Reich|David Reich]], President and COO of [[Mount Sinai Hospital (Manhattan)|Mount Sinai Hospital]], announced in March that the hospital was converting its lobbies into extra patient rooms to \"meet the growing volume of patients\" suffering from coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web|author=Brendan Krisel|url=https://patch.com/new-york/upper-east-side-nyc/mt-sinai-use-lobbies-coronavirus-patient-rooms-report |title=Mt Sinai To Use Lobbies For Coronavirus Patient Rooms: Report &#124; Upper East Side, NY Patch |work=NY Patch|date=March 26, 2020 |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tradeoffs.org/2020/03/31/cc-reich/ |title=Coronavirus Conversations: David Reich |publisher=Tradeoffs|author= Dan Gorenstein|date= March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> Similarly, in April it was announced that the [[Cathedral of St. John the Divine]] in [[Morningside Heights, Manhattan]] would become a field hospital able to care for at least 200 patients, staffed with staff from [[Mount Sinai Morningside]].<ref name=\"nytimes1\">{{cite news|author=Liam Stack |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/06/nyregion/cathedral-st-john-the-divine-coronavirus-field-hospital.html |title=Cathedral of St. John the Divine to Become Emergency Coronavirus Field Hospital - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=2020-04-04 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes1\"/> However, two days later the plan was scrapped for the moment.<ref>[https://abc7ny.com/st-john-cathedral-field-hospital-coronavirus-nyc-update-corona-virus/6089352/]</ref>\n\nAt the request of the Mayor, [[Veterinarian|veterinary clinics]] sent their [[ventilator]]s to human hospitals.<ref name=nyp2020-04-01>{{cite web |last1=Fonrouge |first1=Gabrielle |title=NYC veterinarians forced to choose people over pets in war against coronavirus |url=https://nypost.com/2020/04/01/nyc-vets-forced-to-choose-humans-over-pets-amid-covid-19/ |website=[[New York Post]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403091741/https://nypost.com/2020/04/01/nyc-vets-forced-to-choose-humans-over-pets-amid-covid-19/ |archivedate=April 2, 2020 |language=en |date=April 1, 2020 |quote=Last week, Blue Pearl Veterinary Partners donated seven of their ventilators to New York-Presbyterian Hospital in Manhattan |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn April 5 a state Health Department official confirmed that seriously ill patients were bring treated with hydroxychloroquine. The effects are being observed by the [[University of Albany]]'s School of Public Health.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://nypost.com/2020/04/05/ny-coronavirus-patients-being-treated-with-anti-malarial-drug/ |title=Thousands of NY COVID patients are being treated with anti-malarial drug |date=April 5, 2020 |publisher=The New York Post}}</ref>\n\nOn April 6, the ''New York Times'' reported that the city's overall death rate had tripled and that morgues were overwhelmed. If morgues exceed their capacity, New York City Councilman [[Mark D. Levine]] tweeted that a contingency was that: \"Soon we\u2019ll start \u2018temporary interment.\u2019 This likely will be done by using a NYC park for burials (yes you read that right). Trenches will be dug for 10 caskets in a line.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Marsh |first=Julia |url=https://nypost.com/2020/04/06/nyc-to-begin-temporarily-burying-coronavirus-victims-in-local-parks/ |title=NYC may temporarily bury coronavirus victims on Hart Island |publisher=Nypost.com |date=1970-01-01 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> The mayor's press secretary said that a next resort could be to store or bury bodies on [[Hart Island (Bronx)|Hart Island]] off the coast of the Bronx in the [[Long Island Sound]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Feuer|first=Alan |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/06/nyregion/mass-graves-nyc-parks-coronavirus.html |title=New York City Considers Temporary Graves for Virus Victims|date=2020-04-06|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-07|last2=Stack|first2=Liam |language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Following reports that mass burials had begun there,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52241221|title=New York digging mass graves amid virus outbreak|date=10 April 2020|website=BBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"gothamist2\">{{cite web|url=https://gothamist.com/news/mass-burials-hart-island-increase-fivefold-covid-19-death-toll-skyrockets |title=Mass Burials On Hart Island Increase Fivefold As COVID-19 Death Toll Skyrockets|date=9 April 2020|website=Gothamist |language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200410110654/https://gothamist.com/news/mass-burials-hart-island-increase-fivefold-covid-19-death-toll-skyrockets |archivedate=10 April 2020}}</ref> the mayor clarified that Hart Island was only being used for unclaimed bodies or for those who chose it as a burial place.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/new-york-coronavirus-cases-burials-bodies-covid-19-hart-island-a9459956.html |title=New York rules out mass Covid burials but admits 'devastating' Hart Island pictures are \u2018unclaimed\u2019 victims|date=2020-04-10|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\nDue to the demand from the pandemic on New York City hospitals, for the first time [[Emergency medical services|EMS]] personnel were ordered not to transport adult [[cardiac arrest]] cases to the hospital, if the personnel were unable to restart the patient's heart at the scene.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.salon.com/2020/04/07/first-responders-suspect-crazy-increase-in-cardiac-deaths-in-nyc-is-linked-to-covid-19/?fbclid=IwAR2MfEvJ688AaFHPgVNLSXfnF2e8vskieeOm5yqGBWeAQMRuVS-0MlCnQUg |title=First responders suspect \"crazy increase in cardiac deaths\" in NYC is linked to COVID-19 |publisher=Salon.com |date=1970-01-01 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>  An April 7 news article reported that New York City\u2019s official virus death count was likely far lower than reality, because residents dying at home are not tested for Covid by the [[Office of Chief Medical Examiner of the City of New York|Medical Examiners Office]], and only people whose infection has been confirmed by a Covid test are included in the city health department's official count.<ref name=\"gothamist1\">{{Cite web |url=https://gothamist.com/news/surge-number-new-yorkers-dying-home-officials-suspect-undercount-covid-19-related-deaths |title=Archived copy |access-date=April 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408012523/https://gothamist.com/news/surge-number-new-yorkers-dying-home-officials-suspect-undercount-covid-19-related-deaths |archive-date=April 8, 2020 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[Emergency medical services]] responded to 2,192 deaths at home between March 20 and April 5 (about 130 a day), an almost 400% increase from the same time-period the prior year.<ref name=\"gothamist1\"/>  That number has steadily increased since March 30, with 241 New Yorkers dying at home on April 5 \u2014 more than the number of confirmed COVID-19 deaths citywide that day.<ref name=\"gothamist1\"/> Between March 20 and April 8, an estimated 2,400 more people died untested than the similar period last year.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McCarthy |first1=Craig |title=NYC coronavirus death tally may be short by more than 2,400 people |url=https://nypost.com/2020/04/10/nyc-coronavirus-death-tally-may-be-short-by-more-than-2400-people/ |website=New York Post |language=en |date=10 April 2020}}</ref> New York City Councilman [[Mark D. Levine]], who chairs the city\u2019s Health Committee, said: \"There's no doubt we're undercounting.\"<ref name=\"gothamist1\"/>  Dr. [[Irwin Redlener]], the director of [[Columbia University]]'s National Center for Disaster Preparedness, said \"that\u2019s not okay.\"<ref name=\"gothamist1\"/>\n\n=== Public transport ===\n[[File:MTA New York City Transit Sanitizes Stations and Subway Cars (49618677077).jpg|thumb|Disinfection of [[New York City Subway rolling stock|New York City Subway cars]] against coronavirus]]\nNew York City issued new commuter guidelines amid the current outbreak, asking sick individuals to stay off public transit, encouraging citizens to avoid densely packed buses, [[New York City Subway|subways]], and trains.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/nyc-issues-new-commuter-guidelines-to-combat-coronavirus-spread/2317584/|title=NYC Issues New Commuter Guidelines to Combat Coronavirus Spread|website=NBC New York|language=en-US|access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> Due to decreasing ridership, amid an existing [[2017 New York City transit crisis|transit crisis]], service on buses, subways, and [[commuter rail]] was reduced starting on March 25.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abc7ny.com/6047040/|title=Coronavirus New York: MTA launches essential schedule amid COVID-19 crisis|date=March 24, 2020|website=ABC7 New York|access-date=March 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326080255/https://abc7ny.com/6047040/|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/mta-suspends-some-lines-of-service-amid-coronavirus-staff-shortages/2341550/|title=MTA Slashes Service, NJ Transit on Reduced Schedules|date=March 24, 2020|website=NBC New York|access-date=March 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326033708/https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/mta-suspends-some-lines-of-service-amid-coronavirus-staff-shortages/2341550/|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Education ===\nOn March 8, all school trips were canceled for those in the city.<ref name=\"NewYork38\">[https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2020/03/08/coronavirus-cuomo-testing-kits-connecticut-new-jersey-outbreaks-new-york-cases/ Coronavirus Update: Cuomo Calls For Private Testing To Match Demand, Wife Of New Rochelle Victim Speaks, Schools Close] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309152732/https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2020/03/08/coronavirus-cuomo-testing-kits-connecticut-new-jersey-outbreaks-new-york-cases/ |date=March 9, 2020 }} [[WCBS-TV|CBS 2]]/[[WLNY-TV|WLNY TV 10/55]]</ref> On March 13, De Blasio stated that he would keep the schools open, citing the need for [[School meal|meal program]]s to continue and [[child care]] to continue; [[Los Angeles]] and [[Chicago]] had closed their schools at the end of the prior week.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/coronavirus-outbreak-nyc-teachers-furious-over-de-blasio-s-policy-n1159491|title=Coronavirus outbreak: NYC teachers 'furious' over de Blasio's policy to keep schools open|last=|first=|date=March 13, 2020|website=|publisher=NBCnews.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325232502/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/coronavirus-outbreak-nyc-teachers-furious-over-de-blasio-s-policy-n1159491|archive-date=March 25, 2020|access-date=}}</ref> On March 14, all [[New York Public Library]] branches in the Bronx, Manhattan and Staten Island were temporarily closed for two weeks.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Schuessler|first=Jennifer|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/14/arts/coronavirus-nypl-closed.html|title=At the Library, Last Call for Beauty and Books|date=March 14, 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 26, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326033711/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/14/arts/coronavirus-nypl-closed.html|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Queens Public Library]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://queenseagle.com/all/queens-public-library-closed-until-further-notice|title=Queens Public Library closed until further notice|website=Queens Daily Eagle|language=en-US|access-date=March 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326033712/https://queenseagle.com/all/queens-public-library-closed-until-further-notice|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Brooklyn Public Library]] branches also closed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://patch.com/new-york/prospectheights/brooklyn-public-library-closes-doors-over-coronavirus|title=Brooklyn Public Library Closes Doors Over Coronavirus|date=March 16, 2020|website=Prospect Heights-Crown Heights, NY Patch|language=en|access-date=March 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326033711/https://patch.com/new-york/prospectheights/brooklyn-public-library-closes-doors-over-coronavirus|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The next day, all schools in the [[New York City Department of Education]] system closed until at least mid-April.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Shapiro|first=Eliza|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/15/nyregion/nyc-schools-closed.html|title=New York City Public Schools to Close to Slow Spread of Coronavirus|date=March 15, 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 26, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326170024/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/15/nyregion/nyc-schools-closed.html|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Closed playground in New York City on April 1st, 2020.jpg|thumb|Closed playground in New York City on April 2nd, 2020 due to the 2019-2020 COVID-19 pandemic]]\nOn April 1, Governor Cuomo ordered all playgrounds in the city to be shut in order to promote [[social distancing]]. Parks will remain open.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Barnard |first1=Anne |last2=Schweber |first2=Nate |title=Cooped-Up Children Lose Refuge as N.Y.C. Playgrounds Are Closed |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/01/nyregion/coronavirus-nyc-playgrounds-closed.html?action=click&module=News&pgtype=Homepage |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Crime===\nAt the beginning of March, prior to the confirmation of the first case of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]], and the onset of the coronavirus pandemic in New York City, a 20 percent spike in crime for the first two months of 2020 was reported.<ref>{{cite web|last=DeStefano|first=Anthony M.|url=https://www.newsday.com/news/new-york/nyc-serious-crime-increase-1.42403709|title=Data: NYC serious crimes spikes in first 2 months of 2020|website=[[Newsday]]|date=March 2, 2020|access-date=March 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303190943/https://www.newsday.com/news/new-york/nyc-serious-crime-increase-1.42403709|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> After movement in the city became restricted, [[NYPD]] Commissioner [[Dermot Shea]] stated that the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|public health crisis]] had curtailed crime.<ref>{{cite web|last=Chapman|first=Ben|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-york-city-crime-falls-as-coronavirus-takes-hold-11584998470|title=New York City Crime Falls as Coronavirus Takes Hold|website=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=March 23, 2020|access-date=March 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326034158/https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-york-city-crime-falls-as-coronavirus-takes-hold-11584998470|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> However, by the end of the month, [[9-1-1|911]] calls were at a record high, and 1,048 officers and 145 civilian employees had tested positive for COVID-19. 5,657 uniformed officers, or more than 15% of the force, called out sick on March 31.<ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/01/more-than-1000-new-york-city-police-officers-are-infected-with-coronavirus.html More than 1,000 New York City police officers have the coronavirus as 911 calls hit record highs] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401213545/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/01/more-than-1000-new-york-city-police-officers-are-infected-with-coronavirus.html |date=April 1, 2020 }} by William Feuer, [[CNBC]], April 1, 2020</ref>\n\n==Data==\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/New York State/New York City medical cases chart}}\n{{-}}\n\n==Graphs==\nAdapted from nyc.gov.<ref name=\"nyc_gov_data\" /> Note that the cases are by date of diagnosis, and deaths are by date of death. Due to delays in reporting, historical counts may be subject to change and recent data may be incomplete. \n\n=== Cases over time ===\n<!-- Data lives on Commons. Per talk page, do NOT add counts for the current or previous day, since they are incomplete and can throw off the charts -->\n{{Graph:Lines\n| table=COVID-19 cases in New York City.tab\n| type=time\n| xField=date\n| series=\"cases_per_day\"\n| title=New COVID-19 cases announced each day in New York City\n| yZero=false\n| xAxis=Date\n| xTicks=-\n| yAxis=Confirmed cases\n| yMax=\n| yGrid=y\n| width=1100\n| barwidth=14\n}}\n\n{{Graph:Lines\n| table=COVID-19 cases in New York City.tab\n| type=time\n| xField=date\n| series=\"deaths_per_day\"\n| title=New COVID-19 deaths each day in New York City\n| yZero=false\n| xAxis=Date\n| xTicks=-\n| yAxis=Deaths\n| yMax=\n| yGrid=y\n| width=1100\n| barwidth=14\n}}\n\n=== Cases by demographic ===\n\n{{col-float|1=\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=pie\n|width=100\n|height=100\n|legend=Cases by borough\n|x=Queens (29409), Brooklyn (24635), The Bronx (20265), Manhattan (12088), Staten Island (6979),Unknown (38)\n|y=29409,24635,20265,12088,6979,38\n|showValues=\n}}\n|2=\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=pie\n|width=100\n|height=100\n|legend=Cases by age group\n|x=0 to 17 (1849), 18 to 44 (36102), 45 to 64 (33538), 65 to 74 (11626), 75 and over (10085),Unknown (214)\n|y=1849,36102,33538,11626,10085,214\n|showValues=\n}}\n}}\n<!--choose Pie or Bar chart-->\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type = stackedrect\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n|colors=#0060AB,#F78BA0 \n|width=250\n|xAxisTitle=Age\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|x=Unknown (214), 0 to 17 (1849), 18 to 44 (36102), 45 to 64 (33538), 65 to 74 (11626), 75 and over (10085)\n|yAxisTitle=No. of cases by age group\n|legend=\n|y1= 214,1849,36102,33538,11626,10085\n|y1Title=\n|yGrid= |xGrid=\n}}\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type = stackedrect\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n|colors=#0060AB,#F78BA0 \n|width=250\n|xAxisTitle=Age\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|x=Unknown (), 0 to 17 (3), 18 to 44 (241), 45 to 64 (1143), 65 to 74 (1187), 75 and over (2204)\n|yAxisTitle=No. of deaths\n|legend=Legend\n|y1= 0,3,241,1143,1187,2204\n|y1Title=\n|yGrid= |xGrid=\n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commonscat|COVID-19 pandemic in New York City}}\n\n* [https://www1.nyc.gov/site/doh/covid/covid-19-main.page Coronavirus advice and guidance]\n* [https://www.schools.nyc.gov/school-life/health-and-wellness/coronavirus-update NYC Department of Education]\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|New York City|Pandemic|Viruses}}\n\n[[